	   <a name=96730313631839></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96730313631839><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96730313631839>Buff Management</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96730313631839#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1032><span id= >Ebonygem</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Aug 26th 11:18 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>As a cleric, one of your main tasks in a group is to buff your party members with appropriate blessings - and keep them buffed at all times.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have found that it can be difficult to keep 100% coverage on key buffs either due to mana shortages or not knowing when someone's buffs have faded.  (Yes I know they should speak up, but many times they don't.)  To deal with these problems, I consistently use the management technique below.<br><br>First - when you cast your buffs, cast the same one on each of the party in rapid succession.  Begin with yourself and end with the player you most want to proect (since that will be the last to fade).  By doing this, you will be able to see that a buff is fading on yourself first and know that it will fade in succession on each person.  Often you will be recasting the buff just as people begin to complain that the buff is fading.  (Which, BTW, makes you look even more competent.)  When a new person joins the party in the middle of this sequence, you should buff them up as they join and add them to the rotation - recasting their buffs even if you know they have a considerable time left to run.<br><br>Second -  If you have a big party, you know that recasting all the buffs at once is going to drain your mana to very low levels.  This can be handled by breaking up your buffs - recasting one blessing before you need to, once or twice at first.  <br><br>Third - if you find yourself at full mana and a hard battle is not about to begin, recast one of the buffs even though it has not begun to fade.  My first choice for an early recasting is a cheaper saving throw buff so that I don't add down time to the group.  However, if other members are going to be meditating a long time - go ahead and recast whatever seem most likely to fade next.  <br><br>By doing this technique - you will keep your party continiously buffed and further burnish your reputaion as a cleric.<br><br>May Innoruuk bless your efforts,<br><br><br>Ebonygem Val'Sharess - - RZ<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
