	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96690019823308><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96690019823308>Crowd Control</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96690019823308#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Aug 21st 7:23 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.20]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>It is widely recognized by all, that the enchanter is the one to do crowd control, whenever one of those pulls goes to hell. While he surely is the best equipped to do so, a cleric can do so as well to some extent, especially outside of dungeons.<br><br>The spells to do this with are: Root, Fear, Stun, Lull and Atone (and the various upgrades thereof).<br>Lull (and its upgrades) serve of course to pull only one mob, therefore preventing the dreaded crowd squashing your group by preventing it beforehand. The others are of use, when the screaming mobs are arriving. Fear and Stun can buy your group time (for rooting them, getting a heal off, etc.), the higher froms of fear might even get them beyond their aggro rage, so that they dont return (so seen in the Lake of Ill Omen with the goblins).<br>The best tactic is to root the guys not wanted right NOW, then to Atone them, while all move away from it. If all manage to get beyond aggro, it will leave back to its post.<br>All of these will not stop a real train, but it may make a bad pull at least not fatal. <br>As an example, I had once to use Divine Aura (which de-aggros mobs a bit on you) to give myself a shot at Wave of Fear to buy the druid the time needed to evac us. At another time I managed to enstill and atone 2 drolvargs in Karnor from a pull of 4, which were simply too much at once. <br><br>The whole point is, that you, as a cleric, can do (even if only in limited form) what is necessary to save your party. If you are working as a small group, or even as a team of two, you WILL have to use these spells, so go and train thme a bit, while you have the chance. Even if not ever really needed thenafter, if you know how to do it, you can save your party now and then.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
