<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=96663559729080></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96663559729080><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96663559729080>Dark Elven Cleric 21-45</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96663559729080#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=464><span id= >Vilaraa</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 5:53 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, here is part 2 to my Dark Elven Cleric strategy. I would like to warn that some of the information here may have changed in a recent patch (Ruror's Faction has changed).<br><br>At level 21 I began to learn the fine art of camping and grouping. I will say that camping does not have to be a bad thing at all with the correct group of people. If you do not like the idea of camping then you are in for a rough time of things for part of your Clerics life in EQ.<br><br>Once in the 20s we find ourselves, as clerics, to be underpowered and unwanted. Other wisdom classes get better healing spells and similar buffs and have similar advantages that we do, so this time can be tough. Do not fret. It is the uneducated masses that think this way, and it is our job to let them know that we are best suited for certain tasks. Three of these abilities are the spells Calm, Holy Might and Daring. Need a spawn broken, a cleric can do it. Need a good HP and AC buff you call a cleric, need some stun action. Cleric. Add our healing abilities and it is not long before your group comes to appreciate you as a rounded member of the group and not just a heal/med player.<br><br>I spent most of my early 20s in Rathe Mountains. There are some nice undead camps there that will give you good xp.&nbsp;&nbsp;Giant Skelletons, barbed bone and monk skelletons are nice and can give some nice loot. Our proficiency against undead can really shine here. In your early 20s you can pretty easily get into a group in South Karana killing aviaks (more of the same), but you can also hunt some of the Centaurs that roam the zone as well as get into a group killing Treants. Treants offer up exceptional loot for their level and spawn very fast (2-3 minutes) so you can get a good steady killing there. The downside is that there is almost always a list to get into the group. (more on lists later). Treants will affect your faction with Queynos, but what the hell, those humans are not much more than animals anyways. Both the Treants and Aviaks will take you to level 29 quite easily if you decide to group there and spend some time.<br><br>In your mid-20s, when you are tired of killing those damned aviaks and treants you can also group in Rathe Mountains killing cyclops and group killing gnolls near Splitpaw. You see, the beauty of being the best healer is that you will always be needed in  a real group. At 24 you got Greater Healing so you are the best healer again. Use that to your advantage. You also got new buffs as well. Make your tanks happy and keep everyone healthy. Throw in a little chain casting of your 2 stun spells and break a spawn here or there and you are showing that you are not a heal/med/heal/med machine. I also found that in your mid-20s that it may be time to go into some dungeons. Seeing all these people with magic items and neat stuff will definitely get you heading back to Grobb or Neriak to get provisions. There are 4 nice dungeons that you may want to start checking out in your mid-20s and each is unique in its own way. Upper Guk is home to the Frogloks of Guk, Soluseks Eye (sol a) is home to a clan of gnomes as well as the Solusek Goblins, Najena in Lavastorm is home to Najena and several distinct monsters and Cazic Thule is home to two Lizardman Clans.<br><br>Again, let me stress something. To truely enjoy this game you should always explore. Go places. Do things. Sitting in the same spot will get monotonous. I do encourage all clerics to go to each of these dungeons and see the world. If you do not like a place go to the next. At this point in your life (mid 20s to mid 30s) each of the 4 above dungeons will hold their own dangers and rewards.<br><br>Level 29! I bet you have been waiting for this level. I waited. I watched as I became almost completely useless in meelee combat and my Direct Damage was pitiful compared to other casters. Let me say this... Do not Give up hope on your cleric. Level 29 is your return to glory.<br>The Wrath of Innoruuk is with you now. You get some nice spells (divine barrier, wrath, AC buff, etc) and it is time to use them. At level 29 you can go toe to toe with any other caster and be effective. Other classes have caught up to you in healing power but you now have the offensive power. Someone wants to heal the group, let them. Your turn to break out of the mold. You also get your first resurrection spell (revive) which is a great tool for getting that dead tank back to his body.<br><br>At level 29 I found a few really good places to go if you are open to some risk. Hop on a boat and head on over to Kunark. The Overthere zone is ripe for you at this point. You may wish to avoid casting offensive spells here as everything in the zone will pretty much kick your butt, but you should be able to find a good group and all you need to do is keep em healed. I found a guild to join here that was up to my standards and made alot of friends (that crazy biting and drooling Dark Elf Cleric). If you have trouble here at 29, wait a few levels.<br><br>Another place that I found, if you want to get some decent money and good XP is to kill Druids. Damned tree huggers attack you anyway. East Karana has a druid ring that is just what you need. 3 druid spawn on a 4 minute spawn time. fast and efficient killing. I used this to get me through my first "hell" level and did it in no time. Be warned that killing druids will hurt your faction. level 29 is also a good time to take your first steps into Lower Guk. Lower Guk is a bit tough early on.<br><br>The thing about Lower Guk (and most dungeons as I am sure you know by now) is the Trains. Trains of monsters are a way of life in dungeons. Its how younger players learn "I better not try that again" and older players "damned trains". Lower Guk is nice as it has 2 sides. The Live side with living frogloks, and Dead Side, with Undead Frogloks. I do not need to tell you which side you should try your hand in. Dead Side is awesome. even at 29 working near the zone you get a good feel for the initial layout of the zone. you learn about trains and you learn to manage your mana down to the millisecond keeping your groups alive. You will almost always be able to find a group here and you can, if you really wanted to, stay here all the way until your low 50s in level. Your true power comes though at level 34 with Superior Healing. Nobody gets superior healing but you (except for a few classes who get it after level 50). You also get new Undead DD, hp buff, stun, etc. Other really good places to hunt during your high 20s to low 30s are Frontier Mountains, Lake of Ill Omen and Warsilks Woods. The Kunark zones will have rare spawns that can get you some decent items for your level aswell as some good experience. But beware of spell casters. They can be nasty in Kunark at that level.<br><br>From Level 34-45 the world pretty much opens up for you completely. You will start to become more set into the healing aspect of being a cleric and going into the leadership role in a group. I hear alot of people complain about this and I do not understand why. At level 35 you no longer need to meditate looking at your spellbook so you can watch the action. You learn how to time your spells better, you learn when you need to add that extra nuke into the mix, when you need to chain stun something. You learn how to work solo again with Specters and Hall wanderers in Lower guk.<br><br>The key to success and not being stereo typed is to keep everyone in your group alive. Do NOT let them die. once you have learned to do that without wasting mana and time, you can easily add your other abiliities to a fight. The Froglok Ghoul Lord goes down alot quicker after I have pumped him with 3-4 Expel Undead spells. I always keep my mana in good shape and learn to meditate at all times and learn the pace of your group. Watch everything and keep everyone informed. Keep everyone buffed. Once you earn the trust and respect of those you are fighting with then everyone starts to have more fun as they KNOW that you have them covered.<br><br>During these levels you will want to experience Solusek B and get some Runed Mithril Bracers, Lower Guk, Permafrost, several Kunark Dungeons and outdoor zones. I was not happy being a cleric until I got into the 30s and made some good friends and explored the world. Go to all the places that you want. and remember, kill everything. You are a Dark Elf Cleric Of Pain. Give it out as often as possible because you will get it. Keep everyone healthy and SHOW them some of your other abilities. You will suprise them.<br><br>NOTE- Stun spell.<br>I have spoken with several enchanters about this and it seems to work. Your level 5 spell "stun" will not break a mezmerise because it does not do damage. This is a perfect spell to help your enchanter get a mob off and cast mez. Even if the mob gets mez before your spell hits, it will not break. Try and talk to your enchanters. It can be a real life saver for them.<br><br>NOTE- camping<br>camping can suck but most people who are doing the camping (at least on my server) keep everything fair. The "play nice" rules keep everything open fairly well. The boredom of camping is doing it with a bad group. A good group that camps will not have downtime. Continual pulling and conversation make camping actually fun. Talk to your group. emote them. enjoy the time. make friends. tell stories when you are not fighting. EQ is what you make it. So make it fun.<br><br>NOTE- coming soon:<br>If this is as well received as my Dark Elf Cleric 1-20 article, I will post some of my specific strategies for different dungeons and different mobs as well as group tactics as well as solo tactics for the cleric.<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>Vilaraa Innoruuk<br>45th Cycle of Pain and Devotion<br>Priestess of Pain<br>Wrath of Innoruuk</td></tr>
