	   <a name=96689057711616></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96689057711616><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96689057711616>RE: Creating your cleric: Race</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96689057711616#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Aug 21st 4:42 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I think you're far too generalized here.&nbsp;&nbsp;Your statement about high elves and dwarves is true in the framework that you are measuring them, but it's not strictly fair.  Following are some comments:<br><br>High Elves:  Excellent Wisdom (105), and they don't waste points on unnecessary stats like Dex (though their Int is unnecessarily high).  The only downside is their hideously poor strength, which may become a big factor later when trying to cart around bronze at low levels and Donal's at High levels.  Still, strength is not a HUGE factor.  A very good choice.<br><br>Dwarves: Good Wisdom (93), Great strength and Stamina, terrible agility.  You HAVE to put 5 points into agility with a dwarf, or you will suffer a massive AC hit because of below-average agility (75 is the break-point).  They waste a lot of points in dexterity.  Overall, though, a solid cleric.<br><br>Halflings: Above average Wisdom (90), average strength and stam, exceptional agility (which will help slightly with AC).  Wasted points in Dex.  What they lack in strength and stamina compared to dwarves they make up for with Sneak and Hide, two exceptional skills that will be invaluable throughout your career if used well.<br><br>Human: Average Wisdom (85), Good Strength.  No night vision.  There is no compelling reason to play a human cleric, but there is no reason not too.  The lower wisdom is not that much of a hindrance, especially since they have access to a couple of items the short races cannot wear (ivandyr's hoop, for instance).  I've seen plenty of well played, effective human clerics.  Human clerics of Innoruuk have access to possibly the best quest item in the game for clerics.<br><br>Erudite: Good wisdom (93), poor strength.  No night vision.  Good erudites don't have much going for them other than the sheer coolness factor (a compelling reason by itself).  Evil Erudites, though, have access to some of the best quest cleric equipment available, which more than makes up for their weaknesses (give night vision, strength, AC).<br><br>Dark Elves: Good Wisdom (93), poor strength, very good agility.  Access to (IMO) the best cleric quest item in the game.  Definitely a different experience.<br><br>Gnome: Poor Wisdom (77), poor strength, good agility, a lot of wasted Intelligence.  Has tinkering.  Gnome clerics are few and far between.  Still, there isn't any truly compelling reason NOT to play them.<br><br>From my experience, it's not the amount of Wisdom you have, it's how you use the amount you're given.  The difference between the race with the lowest wis (77) and highest wis (105) ultimately results in the ability to cast Superior heal one more time at 50th level with all else being equal.  Let me put this into perspective:  Pretend a high elf cleric has a 200 wis, and a gnome has a 172 wis.<br><br>The high elf has a total of [(200/5)+2]*50=2100 mana, meaning he can cast superior heal 8 times and have 100 mana left over.<br><br>The gnome has [(172/5)+2]*50=1820 mana, meaning he can cast superior heal 7 times and have 70 mana left over.<br><br>Quite frankly, the difference isn't that large at all.  The main objective in picking a class is choosing something you'll be happy with.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
