<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=96661500329131></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96661500329131><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96661500329131>Dealing with aggro</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=7&mid=96661500329131#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=581><span id=Sage>Calimyr</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>22 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 12:10 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.29]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>You may hear echoed many times about how large taunts our heals are. This is true to an extent, but dealing with it is a large part of being a cleric, and it isn't insurmountable.<br><br>Hate from the primary target. This usually isn't a problem. When the puller grabs the first mob, he is typically wedged into their hatelist (some mobs that train off easily, like bats/bugs or undead, are more the exception than the rule). About the only time you'll taunt this is a few cases. If you heal just as the puller returns, before he has damaged the npc, you'll sometimes draw its aggro. If you wait for the tanks to engage the mob, even an early large heal should not frenzy it on you (as long as the tanks are taunting and such, of course). Secondly,iIf you heal a much, much lower level target with a large heal. By ratio, this has a huge taunt, so don't be surprised if when you superior heal a newbie fighting an orc pawn, the orc pawn decides to attack you. This doesn't really come up that often, but can be annoying for a newbie you decide to random help when the thing takes off at full speed from half-health. Thirdly, in very large raids (say, 18 or so melee?), with how the hatelist is limited, it is somewhat easier to go to the top of the hatelist. This can be annoying, as for relatively minor things that would never aggro under normal circumstances, you may be summoned and beaten around a bit.<br><br>Anyways, aggro from primary target is rare, if it happens ever. Sometimes clerics may make it sounds like this happens all the time- I don't think this has happened to me more than a dozen or so times in my career, mostly from the 3rd reason.<br><br>Now, the real time we get aggro'd. In multiple pulls, if the puller targets one, brings it back, and everyone sets in on the primary target. Assist is important, etc, all well in good. What happens when you heal then, of course? Well, mobs 2, 3, and 4 don't have the substantial hate that the first mob does towards the tanks. That first heal is likely to taunt all the other ones.<br><br>Fortunately, there is an awful lot you can do to deal with this. The easiest is to just work with an enchanter. Heck, in some circumstances you prefer to taunt them onto yourself with for a second, so the enchanter can get an uninterrupted mesmerization off without the resisting ones beating on him. On easier pulls, he'll taunt early by tashing the other ones to single them out with his single target mez. Help him out by timing your stuns so the targets won't interrupt his castings. If need be, drag taunted away mobs and stun/root park them away.<br><br>If not with an enchanter (or feign puller, or even bard or necro), there are a couple things you can do in multiple pulls. One is to have the puller damage each thing as he brings them back, and possibly a bit during combat. This will have the tank tanking however many things down, but give you ample time to heal and med (though be careful about taunting them to you by sitting in too close proximity to them... the more room you have to operate, the better). The problem with this method is that the tank can often, well, die on difficult pulls. Though better the tank than a total party wipeout.<br><br>Lastly, I would do root/parking. Not a replacement for an enchanter by any stretch, and I usually lean towards the tank tanking down multiple things instead to give more time for med ticks, but sometimes this is better. Don't be afraid to be decently stun heavy if you go this route (stun and holy might should do it most often), and I generally stick with immobilize. This might take some practice, but it isn't really that terrible of a solution.:)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
