	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 11:46 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.42]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>In my mind, there are 3 ideals for group selection which makes our job as clerics far, far easier. In order of preference these are: First, an enchanter. Crowd control, besides making fights vastly easier, safer, and more efficient also lets us play with a certainty and precision that we couldn't otherwise. If 4 things are dazzled, they won't be coming up earlier than 2 minutes from the dazzle... the exact nature of mes duration gives us a lot of room to operate. We know that we can start complete healing when the tank is at a half bubble, because there is no chance of something whapping us and interrupting a critical spell, and so on. You can come close to this without an enchanter, but in my opinion there are too many variables that can skew that. There is also slows and aug/speeds they bring to the group that further speeds up the group kill rate, but that isn't as important to us as clerics as the group as a whole (like the remaining slots of a group in a standard 6 person).<br><br>Second, a shaman. Though the slows of an enchanter are extremely helpful, the yawns of a shaman (especially turgor's) are amazing. This lightening the load off the enchanter is no small benefit as well, and I consider a shaman an asset in addition to, not a replacement for, an enchanter. Secondly, talisman and even stamina make your complete heals greatly more efficient, which can substantially speed up your kill rate even without yawns.<br><br>Thirdly, and what I consider the least important asset, but what many clerics (and I think misguidedly) consider the most important, is the quality of the tank. I feel that an ogre warrior in mostly cobalt with some indo, using a twig/jade mace and such is nice, but not a requirement. I'd much rather be in a group with a mid 40s ranger in ivy etched as the primary tank, but with a good 51st level enchanter, than I would with a solid low 50s warrior but another caster subbing for an enchanter. The swing from an enchanter, depending on what you are fighting, should never be underestimated.<br><br>All that set up said, how should you play under ideal conditions? Well, with what I consider a standard group (3 or so melee, enchanter, me, and typically a random caster... unfortunately usually not a shaman), I feel that you should put the highest symbol available on the primary tank (naltron or mazrin respectively on your level), heroism, and the highest AC buff you have (shield of words for most of us). For the secondary and so on melees, I'd go with heroism, highest ac buff (to minimize damage, is mana efficient over the duration I feel), and probably pizarn (depending on the intensity of the fighting, and how quickly we need to buff up. 3 naltrons and 3 shields itself is substantial set up time). For the enchanter, naltron/mazrin and heroism. AC buff is dicey. If you are already having mana issues from setup, then I'd have the enchanter cast his AC buff on himself and the non-tanks, follow'd by aug. Though in truly dangerous situations I'd go with the highest possible AC buff on an enchanter, in most convential grinds using the mana to do it may only result in slowing you down. For myself and other casters, heroism, nothing else. (in terms of resist spells, this all assumes we'll be fighting mostly melee. Resists as needed, of course). Unless you think that you are going to be in a dangerous enough situation that you feel the casters will die without a symbol, it just isn't worth the mana for that extra margin of safety.<br><br>After setup, complete heal should be mainline heal. Neither remedy or DL approaches its efficiency. Even on sub 50 tanks, you can frequently get 2000 points of healing or so off a CH. With a shaman, its more like 2400 or so. Post 50, it becomes even more extreme, and with clarity and slows also tremendously adding to your mana efficiency, as long as you stick to Complete Heals with full buffs up, you should be riding high on mana.<br><br>In fact, TOO high on mana often. With ideal groupping conditions, I find myself at near full mana even in large pulls (5+) when I need to spend a good deal of time keeping the enchanter alive. This in turn has the effect of letting us use our mana to further speed up the group. Starting to stagger rebuffs so there isn't a low mana rebuffing period that causes a lapse in pulling. Past that, you can even nuke at FM to speed up the kill rate a touch, or even helping the enchanter's mana on consistent large pulls by helping to put one thing down fast.<br><br>The trap to avoid is ever chain-remedying. Very few mobs even post kunark can kill a tank (even a ranger) in 10 seconds. Even if they are not slowed, as long as the target is fully buffed, you can start a CH pretty high and avoid blowing half your mana on chain-remedies or lights that will oom you. The careful thing is to make sure then that the tanks don't do a lot of switching on you, or you could start a CH on a warrior then to have the ranger immediately taunt onto himself and then _have_ to be chain-remedied after you duck-out a worthless CH.<br><br>Hope this helps,<br>Cal<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
